course_metadata.title: Nonlinear mechanics of low-carbon concrete structures

content_chunks.content: The non-linear deformation of reinforced concrete structures may result in several times higher displacements in comparison to linear elastic analysis. This is mainly caused by the complex interaction of reinforcement and concrete, cracking and time-dependant effects of creep and shrinkage. In the present course, main aspects of nonlinear behaviour of reinforced concrete are discussed along with the analysis methods.

Nonlinear mechanics technology for accurate structural analysis of low-carbon concrete systems - this course delivers comprehensive expertise in analyzing complex concrete behavior through advanced finite element methods and material modeling techniques. Students master concrete microstructure analysis, reinforcement-concrete bond mechanics, and cracking analysis methods that predict structural performance under various loading conditions. The curriculum covers physical and geometrical nonlinearity, iterative analysis methods, layer section models, and time-dependent effects including creep and shrinkage phenomena. Graduates emerge skilled in implementing nonlinear finite element analysis, stress-strain evaluation, and deformation prediction techniques that enable accurate structural design of sustainable low-carbon concrete constructions while accounting for complex material interactions and long-term performance characteristics.

content_chunks.title: Introduction to non-linear analysis: physical and geometrical nonlinearity. Evaluation of nonlinear effects in the design of reinforced concrete structures
Causes of concrete physical non-linearity: concrete microstructure, microcracking, movement of moisture
Nonlinear behaviour of tensile and compressive concrete
Non-linear finite element analysis of reinforced concrete: assumptions, material models, evaluation of the results
Bond of reinforcement and concrete: stress and strain analysis in composite and bond-slip zones
Deformation stages of tensile reinforced concrete element: stress-transfer and cracking
Application of average stress - average strain diagrams for analysis of reinforced concrete elements
Iterative analysis methods: assumptions, algorithms. Application of layer section model
Cracking analysis in reinforced concrete: assumptions, methods of analysis
Deformation and cracking analysis of flexural reinforced concrete elements
Time-dependant effects in reinforced concrete: creep and shrinkage. Influence these effects on the stress and strain state of reinforced concrete elements
